│ stop({"edit_points": [[1055, 1064, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.h"]], │
│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop vectorizer crashes in      │
│ VPlanTransforms::dropPoisonGeneratingRecipes with an assertion that an        │
│ instruction with poison-generating flags is not covered by                    │
│ VPRecipeWithIRFlags. The reproducer involves a call to llvm.fabs with the     │
│ nnan flag. During VPlan construction, we create VP recipes that are supposed  │
│ to carry IR flags so that dropPoisonGeneratingRecipes can strip them when     │
│ required. The assertion indicates that the recipe being visited is not        │
│ recognized as VPRecipeWithIRFlags, yet its underlying instruction carries     │
│ poison-generating flags (e.g., nnan), leading to the mismatch.\n\n2.          │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash happens at VPlanTransforms.cpp:1926, inside   │
│ the lambda in dropPoisonGeneratingRecipes. The code first tries to            │
│ dyn_cast<VPRecipeWithIRFlags>(CurRec). If this fails, it asserts that the     │
│ underlying IR instruction does not have poison-generating flags. Since we     │
│ have nnan on a call to llvm.fabs, that condition fails. The reproducer’s      │
│ first transformation point is dropPoisonGeneratingRecipes, which matches the  │
│ stack and indicates the issue is at the identification of recipes carrying    │
│ flags.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nVPWidenIntrinsicRecipe is a subclass of    │
│ VPRecipeWithIRFlags and is used to model widening of intrinsics such as       │
│ llvm.fabs. However, VPRecipeWithIRFlags::classof currently does not include   │
│ VPDef IDs for VPWidenIntrinsicSC, VPWidenCallSC, or VPWidenSelectSC (and      │
│ possibly others). As a result, dyn_cast<VPRecipeWithIRFlags>(CurRec) returns  │
│ false for these recipes, and the code takes the else branch with the          │
│ assertion. The underlying CallInst for fabs has nnan set, which are           │
│ poison-generating flags, causing the assertion. Therefore, the recipe         │
│ hierarchy is correct, but the classof dispatch omits these recipe IDs,        │
│ breaking type identification.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.h\n- Location:                            │
│ VPRecipeWithIRFlags::classof (lines ~1055-1064 in the provided snippet)\n-    │
│ Change: Add missing VPDef IDs to classof so that VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe,      │
│ VPWidenCallRecipe, and VPWidenSelectRecipe (and any other recipes deriving    │
│ from VPRecipeWithIRFlags that carry IR flags) are recognized.\n\nProposed     │
│ patch (conceptual):\nModify VPRecipeWithIRFlags::classof to include:\n        │
│ R->getVPDefID() == VPRecipeBase::VPWidenIntrinsicSC ||\n  R->getVPDefID() ==  │
│ VPRecipeBase::VPWidenCallSC ||\n  R->getVPDefID() ==                          │
│ VPRecipeBase::VPWidenSelectSC\nin addition to the existing cases              │
│ (VPInstructionSC, VPWidenSC, VPWidenEVLSC, VPWidenGEPSC, VPWidenCastSC,       │
│ VPReplicateSC, VPReverseVectorPointerSC, VPVectorPointerSC).\n\nThis ensures  │
│ that dyn_cast<VPRecipeWithIRFlags> succeeds for recipes that actually store   │
│ and need to manage IR flags, and dropPoisonGeneratingFlags will properly      │
│ clear poison-generating flags (e.g., nnan) when necessary, preventing the     │
│ assertion.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to incomplete type filtering   │
│ in VPRecipeWithIRFlags::classof, which fails to recognize                     │
│ VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe (and similar) as carrying IR flags. Extending classof  │
│ to include VPWidenIntrinsicSC, VPWidenCallSC, and VPWidenSelectSC fixes the   │
│ mismatch, allowing dropPoisonGeneratingRecipes to operate correctly and       │
│ prevents the assertion. This aligns with the assumption that assertions are   │
│ correct and reveals an earlier error in type identification."})               │
